			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">I think the reason glibc uses "-include" instead of "include" is this:
Suppose you change Makerules or make_sysd_rules.py so that the
generated sysd-rules is syntactically invalid.  If you then fix these
files and re-run, make will still exit with an error, and you will
have to manually delete sysd-rules and re-run.

This doesn't seem like a good enough reason to ignore errors, though.
